WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.400 --> 00:00:10.880
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Good morning everyone, and welcome
yet another attempt at The App Clinic of video

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:12.510
players.

00:00:12.510 --> 00:00:18.210
But before we get started, you know, we're
going to be reviewing these video player apps.

00:00:18.210 --> 00:00:20.840
And frankly I don't really understand what
the big deal is.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:22.410
I mean, I've had a look at the code.

00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:25.839
And as far as I can see, this is all we need
to do, right?

00:00:25.839 --> 00:00:31.099
We just need to, you know, get a video to
view, put it somewhere on my screen, and then

00:00:31.099 --> 00:00:34.730
it's just a simple matter of passing in different
URLs, right?

00:00:34.730 --> 00:00:37.770
I mean, if that's all there is too it, what's
the challenge?

00:00:37.770 --> 00:00:39.940
Why are there--why are these apps popular?

00:00:39.940 --> 00:00:43.190
Why can't people just, you know, build it
themselves.

00:00:43.190 --> 00:00:44.190
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Sure.

00:00:44.190 --> 00:00:45.660
Your ignorance astounds me.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:52.280
You might think that of course, having a video
view that's so easy to use would make it very

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:53.800
easy to write a video app.

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:54.800
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:58.800
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: The truth is in software, things
that are very easy to use are often not very

00:00:58.800 --> 00:00:59.800
powerful.

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:03.530
And that's exactly the way that video player
turned out.

00:01:03.530 --> 00:01:10.750
Now, we started way back in the--in the early
days of Android, with media playback via the

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:11.850
MediaPlayer API.

00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:17.220
Of course, that's what we just saw with this
sim, that's actually a one call fire and forget

00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:19.100
way of playing back video.

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:22.110
A MediaPlayer is really easy to use.

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:26.920
But it's probably too easy to use, especially
if you're looking for professional custom

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:28.030
solutions.

00:01:28.030 --> 00:01:29.420
It's basically a black box.

00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:31.990
If you have any kind of special needs, you're
out luck.

00:01:31.990 --> 00:01:35.990
For instance, MediaPlayer is hardware accelerated.

00:01:35.990 --> 00:01:41.190
But, it's hardware accelerated differently
on different platforms, on different versions

00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:43.460
EOS and different OEM devices.

00:01:43.460 --> 00:01:47.680
And there's no way to find out what type of
hardware acceleration you're getting.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:48.680
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Huh.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:52.979
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Now, that's not really a problem
if you don't want customization because you're

00:01:52.979 --> 00:01:59.770
always guaranteed that an Android device will
playback H2--H.264 baseline profile.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:03.610
A lot of people don't like baseline profile
though especially people who have already

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:05.680
encoded for other devices.

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:07.390
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Shocked.

00:02:07.390 --> 00:02:12.230
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: So, when we launched Honeycomb,
we decided to make some improvements and we

00:02:12.230 --> 00:02:14.840
supported an API called OpenMAX AL.

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:22.069
Now, the truth is OpenMAX AL was not necessarily
our first choice because it's not a Java API.

00:02:22.069 --> 00:02:28.189
But, it is a cron standard, much like OpenGL
and allowed us to get some of the professional

00:02:28.189 --> 00:02:30.010
features that we were looking for.

00:02:30.010 --> 00:02:35.439
So, if you wanted professional features in
Honeycomb and in Ice Cream Sandwich, OpenMAX

00:02:35.439 --> 00:02:36.680
AL is a great choice.

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:42.919
The drawback is you've got to write your code
in C. With Ice Cream Sandwich we also introduced

00:02:42.919 --> 00:02:50.249
a new way of working with video, and that
was the texture review and service view.

00:02:50.249 --> 00:02:56.860
So these--the ability to actually work with
video textures allowed you to do some more

00:02:56.860 --> 00:02:59.529
interesting things like real time video effects.

00:02:59.529 --> 00:03:00.829
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Nice.

00:03:00.829 --> 00:03:05.620
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: But things didn't really get
real until Jelly Bean.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:11.019
Jelly Bean is the apotheosis of video APIs,
by which I mean we have a Java API that works.

00:03:11.019 --> 00:03:12.019
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Nice.

00:03:12.019 --> 00:03:15.040
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Jelly Bean supports what we call
MediaCodec.

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:19.709
A MediaCodec is not an easy to use API by
any means.

00:03:19.709 --> 00:03:25.730
But it's a sort of API that if you are a professional
that writes video apps for a living and understands

00:03:25.730 --> 00:03:27.489
media.

00:03:27.489 --> 00:03:31.889
You're going to love it or at least hate it
considerably less.

00:03:31.889 --> 00:03:34.899
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Minimizing hate factor, that's what
we're all about.

00:03:34.899 --> 00:03:35.899
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:03:35.899 --> 00:03:40.420
It gives you low level access to the media
acceleration hardware and it gives you an

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:42.870
API to query what formats the hardware supports.

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:46.169
So like I said, it's not a simple API by any
means.

00:03:46.169 --> 00:03:55.079
But it is professional and it supports most
of the used cases and corner cases that a

00:03:55.079 --> 00:03:57.599
really nice video player needs.

00:03:57.599 --> 00:04:00.409
And we'll see some of those used cases as
we look at the apps.

00:04:00.409 --> 00:04:06.480
For instance, as I mentioned media player
will only hardware accelerate certain formats.

00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:07.480
&gt;&gt; MEIER: I see.

00:04:07.480 --> 00:04:10.489
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: And you don't necessarily know
what formats those are.

00:04:10.489 --> 00:04:16.710
So, it's impossible with media player to make
an application that claims to support every

00:04:16.710 --> 00:04:19.489
format or even a large number of formats.

00:04:19.489 --> 00:04:23.530
And I think, we noticed that one of the selling
points to the players that we're looking at

00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:27.160
today, is how many different media formats
they support.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:28.160
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:31.539
That was one of the biggest things which most
of them claimed, was which media formats they

00:04:31.539 --> 00:04:32.539
support...

00:04:32.539 --> 00:04:33.539
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:04:33.539 --> 00:04:34.539
&gt;&gt; MEIER: ...being able to play things back.

00:04:34.539 --> 00:04:39.310
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: And without MediaCodec, your
stuck with two unattractive choices.

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:47.810
You can either only support the baseline formats
that are hardware accelerated across all Android

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:48.810
devices.

00:04:48.810 --> 00:04:49.810
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Uh-hmm.

00:04:49.810 --> 00:04:53.480
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Or you do everything with a software
decoder and don't support hardware decoding

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:54.480
at all.

00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:55.480
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Right.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:56.709
And that's going to result in worse playback,
right?

00:04:56.709 --> 00:05:02.790
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: In general, or at the very least
a lower battery life, because a software implementation

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:05.480
is going to require a lot more power since...

00:05:05.480 --> 00:05:06.480
&gt;&gt; MEIER: That makes sense.

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:10.169
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: ...it's being done the CPU and
you know, less efficient SOC--part of the

00:05:10.169 --> 00:05:11.169
SOC.

00:05:11.169 --> 00:05:12.169
&gt;&gt; MEIER: There you go.

00:05:12.169 --> 00:05:13.169
That was educational.

00:05:13.169 --> 00:05:14.169
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Indeed.

00:05:14.169 --> 00:05:18.120
So let's talk about, if you decided to make
a media app.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:19.120
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Indeed.

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:20.300
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: What should it be?

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:21.300
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:23.349
So, let's have a look.

00:05:23.349 --> 00:05:25.870
So these are the--these are the criteria which
we are looking for.

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:29.879
The prescriptions if you will for making a
great video player app.

00:05:29.879 --> 00:05:33.449
And I think we want to break this down into
two general categories.

00:05:33.449 --> 00:05:34.449
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Sure.

00:05:34.449 --> 00:05:40.380
These are the main two pieces of functionality
that every video app we looked at has.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:41.380
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Exactly.

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:44.830
And you'll note also that we--the apps that
we're looking at here are video players.

00:05:44.830 --> 00:05:49.801
So this is apps where you're playing back
video that you've already downloaded, put

00:05:49.801 --> 00:05:53.719
on to your device somehow rather than apps
which are designed for discovering content.

00:05:53.719 --> 00:05:54.719
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:05:54.719 --> 00:05:56.629
So this isn't Hulu or Netflix.

00:05:56.629 --> 00:06:02.039
This isn't a Google Play or a streaming service.

00:06:02.039 --> 00:06:06.650
This is all about, you've gotten video, you
know, from your camcorder or you downloaded

00:06:06.650 --> 00:06:08.740
it from one of these sources.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:10.240
And you want to take a look at it.

00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:11.240
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Exactly.

00:06:11.240 --> 00:06:13.360
So there's--the two categories are Browsing
and Playback.

00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:15.980
So for Browse, it's really about easy organization.

00:06:15.980 --> 00:06:19.560
It's about being able to discover the information
that you've already got on your device.

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:22.760
And so you've got one or two videos, then
that should be really straight forward.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:24.689
But, you've got to think in terms of scale.

00:06:24.689 --> 00:06:28.810
What if you've got, you know, tens or hundreds
of videos that you want to be able to browse

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:29.810
through.

00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:30.810
What's that experience like?

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:32.219
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: You know, we sort of went through
a lot of this with audio...

00:06:32.219 --> 00:06:33.219
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:06:33.219 --> 00:06:38.520
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: ...playback apps when we talked
about those about a month ago and how one

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:43.500
thing that can make or break an app is how
easy it is to discover the content that you

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:46.250
want to play and ignore the content that you
don't.

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:51.280
And one of the most important things that
a video app can do in the browse mode is,

00:06:51.280 --> 00:06:57.449
respect to the .nomedia file, that a lot of
game developers for instance will download

00:06:57.449 --> 00:07:06.319
a bunch of AVIs or MPEG4s to a media directory,
so that they can play it later on in the game.

00:07:06.319 --> 00:07:12.150
Now, because that's not a universally accessible
global media directory that's meant to be

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:13.150
played by anyone.

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:14.150
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Uh-hmm.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:20.229
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: They'll stick a .nomedia file
inside that directory, and if you don't respect

00:07:20.229 --> 00:07:21.229
that.

00:07:21.229 --> 00:07:22.229
&gt;&gt; MEIER: You need a little noise.

00:07:22.229 --> 00:07:23.229
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Oh, absolutely.

00:07:23.229 --> 00:07:26.080
You're going to get cut scenes from games
that you didn't even know existed.

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:28.210
And a lot times they don't have very informative
names.

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:29.210
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Sure.

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:30.220
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: That ends up being kind of a
spoiler really.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:31.220
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Yeah.

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:34.169
And you don't know what that is until it's
the end scene from a game that you're halfway

00:07:34.169 --> 00:07:35.169
through playing.

00:07:35.169 --> 00:07:36.169
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Yup.

00:07:36.169 --> 00:07:37.169
&gt;&gt; MEIER: So as...

00:07:37.169 --> 00:07:38.719
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Thanks a lot, Bard's Tale is
ruined for me.

00:07:38.719 --> 00:07:41.979
&gt;&gt; MEIER: In terms of playback, it's kind
of what you'd expect.

00:07:41.979 --> 00:07:46.090
And again, what we've sort of described already
in terms of why you're building these apps

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:47.090
to begin with.

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:50.020
And it's the ability to be able to play back
pretty much anything.

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:52.949
So I don't want to have to think about what
the codecs are, how it's being transcoded.

00:07:52.949 --> 00:07:56.080
I just want to copy stuff onto the device
and have it played back.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:57.080
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Uh-hmm.

00:07:57.080 --> 00:08:00.629
&gt;&gt; MEIER: And I wanted to it efficiently as
well, so hardware decoding where possible.

00:08:00.629 --> 00:08:01.910
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:05.060
I also wanted to have my app support subtitles.

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:09.520
This is really important for hearing impaired
people.

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:13.090
To me, it's important because I like to watch
foreign language films.

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:16.569
My wife does not speak English as a foreign
or as a first language.

00:08:16.569 --> 00:08:17.569
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Uh-hmm.

00:08:17.569 --> 00:08:19.770
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: You have some problems with American
I believe Reto, so...

00:08:19.770 --> 00:08:20.770
&gt;&gt; MEIER: That's right.

00:08:20.770 --> 00:08:21.770
It can get confusing.

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:22.770
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Absolutely.

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:24.370
So, you need to have those subtitles just
incase.

00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:25.770
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:08:25.770 --> 00:08:30.529
And the last thing we wanted to talk about
was the notification bar or status bar.

00:08:30.529 --> 00:08:35.270
Being the real one, and we saw a lot of apps
trying to sort of, half take our advice here

00:08:35.270 --> 00:08:38.602
and say, "Oh well people say that they want
to have their status bar visible because they

00:08:38.602 --> 00:08:39.919
want to see what the time is.

00:08:39.919 --> 00:08:44.180
They want to see, you know, that sort of information,
battery life, wifi connectivity..."

00:08:44.180 --> 00:08:45.230
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Well and of course they weren't
taking our advice.

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:47.960
I mean, these are features these apps have
had for a long time.

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:48.960
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Yeah, apparently.

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:52.800
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: It's obvious that people want
to be able to see the sorts of things that

00:08:52.800 --> 00:08:56.770
they see in a notification bar, battery life
and the clock being two very important once.

00:08:56.770 --> 00:08:57.770
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:08:57.770 --> 00:08:59.800
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: But if you're going to show that
already.

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:01.950
Why not just support all of these cases.

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:05.660
When I have a notification, I want to be able
to pull it down.

00:09:05.660 --> 00:09:10.710
I want to know if I need to stop watching
my video because there's an important meeting

00:09:10.710 --> 00:09:11.889
that I completely forgot about.

00:09:11.889 --> 00:09:12.889
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Absolutely.

00:09:12.889 --> 00:09:15.740
So let's have a look at the apps which we're
going to check out today.

00:09:15.740 --> 00:09:19.870
So the poor app developers for these apps
who have been waiting for two or three weeks

00:09:19.870 --> 00:09:24.900
now for this feedback, but we're going to
be looking at MX Player, CineXPlayer and DICE

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:25.900
player.

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:28.360
So three video playing apps there.

00:09:28.360 --> 00:09:30.980
So, let's get started, I guess.

00:09:30.980 --> 00:09:31.980
Let's kick off of it.

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:33.580
The first step we wanted to look at was CineXPlayer.

00:09:33.580 --> 00:09:34.580
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Uh-hmm.

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:39.620
&gt;&gt; MEIER: And as you can see we've got the--they've
got a feature graphic which is really nice.

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:45.280
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Yeah, and the feature graphic
here is nicely done.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:48.960
But, I wouldn't use this one personally.

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:52.680
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Yeah, I mean, you can see we're
looking at a confidence model.

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:53.760
It's from a fair distance away.

