&gt;&gt; MEIER: Indeed.

00:28:44.460 --> 00:28:47.830
So, one of the things which I really like
about MX Player was the fact that it handled

00:28:47.830 --> 00:28:49.380
that immersive experience correctly.

00:28:49.380 --> 00:28:50.380
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:28:50.380 --> 00:28:53.121
&gt;&gt; MEIER: So, we got rid of all of my cron,
but then brought it all back as soon as I

00:28:53.121 --> 00:28:54.121
pressed the button.

00:28:54.121 --> 00:28:58.760
And so if you're wondering how to I do that,
well, here's the code that tells you.

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:04.790
So, for Android 4 and above, what you want
to do is actually set the system visibility

00:29:04.790 --> 00:29:06.520
options to SYSTEM_UI_FLAG_HIDE_NAVIGATION.

00:29:06.520 --> 00:29:13.320
So, what that will do was actually remove
all the cron, the status bar, the navigation,

00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:17.480
the notification bar, everything on Android
4 devices.

00:29:17.480 --> 00:29:21.780
And you'll note that at the same time as we
set that flag we're also going to set a listener

00:29:21.780 --> 00:29:25.500
which is going to set the UI flag either visible
or full screen.

00:29:25.500 --> 00:29:30.380
So, that's going to remove your notification
bar on phone devices as opposed to tablets.

00:29:30.380 --> 00:29:31.380
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Uh-hmm.

00:29:31.380 --> 00:29:34.430
&gt;&gt; MEIER: And so this is the neatest way and
that's what we're seeing on this device.

00:29:34.430 --> 00:29:39.110
If you go back before that on Android 3, so
Honeycomb devices, it's a little bit different.

00:29:39.110 --> 00:29:45.260
We have--we have the ability to hide the status
bar and we also have the ability to go into

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:49.240
what's kind of a low--a low profile mode.

00:29:49.240 --> 00:29:54.299
And so this is going to eliminate your status
bar, your notification bar on the phone devices

00:29:54.299 --> 00:29:59.860
and it's going to make your navigation on
Honeycomb devices be those three little dots.

00:29:59.860 --> 00:30:04.080
So, it hides as much as it can but doesn't
actually give you any extra screen real estate.

00:30:04.080 --> 00:30:05.080
&gt;&gt; NI-LEWIS: Right.

00:30:05.080 --> 00:30:06.080
This is what we use to call lights-out mode.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:07.080
&gt;&gt; MEIER: Exactly.

00:30:07.080 --> 00:30:08.080
Lights-out mode.

00:30:08.080 --> 00:30:11.590
So, that's kind of your next best for sort
of the Honeycomb ear devices.

00:30:11.590 --> 00:30:17.309
If you go back one step further before we
had tablet devices nearly--currently, you

00:30:17.309 --> 00:30:20.030
had on the screen at all, was the status bar.

00:30:20.030 --> 00:30:24.300
The way to do that, was to flag full screen,
you know, set the window layer [INDISTINCT]

00:30:24.300 --> 00:30:30.559
flag full screen and that will remove your
notification bar and this is something which

00:30:30.559 --> 00:30:34.410
is only appropriate to do in a very specific
circumstances in playing back video is one

00:30:34.410 --> 00:30:35.410
of those circumstances.

00:30:35.410 --> 00:30:41.370
And the important thing to note here for pre-Honeycomb
devices is that you have to manually add it

00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:42.370
and remove it.

00:30:42.370 --> 00:30:45.080
And so one of the temptations that I've seen
in a lot of apps do is they simply remove

00:30:45.080 --> 00:30:46.690
it and you never get it back.

00:30:46.690 --> 00:30:49.799
So, even while you're browsing when if you're
not, even doing video playback, you're going

00:30:49.799 --> 00:30:51.870
to still have your notifications, that's infuriating.

00:30:51.870 --> 00:30:57.480
So, what you actually want to do here is tie
this code into play and pause of your media.

00:30:57.480 --> 00:31:01.740
So, whenever you're playing you can hide the
notifications and soon you pause, you bring

00:31:01.740 --> 00:31:03.179
it back again.

